\begin_layout Standard
What does it mean to model log-normal data?
 What we are saying is that we have some variable,
 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

,
 which is 
\begin_inset Formula $\log_{b}$
\end_inset

-normally
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that throughout I use 
\begin_inset Formula $\log_{a}$
\end_inset

to indicate logarithm to the base 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 since these calculations work regardless of the base used.
 When the distribution is referred to informally (i.e.,
 non-mathematically) I drop the base.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 distributed so 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\sim\log_{b}N(\mu,\sigma^{2})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is the logarithm of the mean and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 is the base 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 logarithm of the variance of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 This is equivalent to defining a variable 
\begin_inset Formula $Z=b^{Y}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\sim N(\mu_{*},\sigma_{*}^{2})$
\end_inset

.
 The log-normal distribution is useful in cases where 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is defined over the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,\infty]$
\end_inset

 (i.e.,
 
\begin_inset Formula $Y>0$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Canonical references for the log-normal distribution include 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "aitchison_lognormal_1957"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "crow_lognormal_1988"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Arithmetic versus geometric means
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can estimate estimate the expectation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}(Y)$
\end_inset

 by either an 
\shape italic
arithmetic
\shape default
 or 
\shape italic
geometric
\shape default
 mean (denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}_{A}(Y)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}_{G}(Y)$
\end_inset

,
 respectively).
 These are defined as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathbb{E}_{A}(Y) & =b^{\mu+\frac{1}{2}\sigma^{2}}\quad\text{and}\label{eq:arithmean}\\
\mathbb{E}_{G}(Y) & =b^{\mu}.\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

Where the geometric 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

mean
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 corresponds to the median of the distribution.
 This difference is shown in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:dist-arith-vs-geom"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

