\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Demonstration of the differences in estimation of arithmetic vs geometric means for log-normal,
 overlaid on the distribution functions.
 Parameters are given on the 
\begin_inset Formula $\log_{e}$
\end_inset

 scale,
 as required by the R function 
\family typewriter
dlnorm
\family default
.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:dist-arith-vs-geom"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly,
 we define the arithmetic and geometric standard deviations as follows:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\text{SD}_{A}(Y) & =b^{\mu+\frac{1}{2}\sigma^{2}}\sqrt{b^{\sigma^{2}}-1}\\
\text{SD}_{G}(Y) & =b^{\sigma}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Following usual results,
 we have that multiplication of log-normal distributed variables results in a log-normally distributed product and therefore geometric means of log-normally distributed variables are log-normally distributed.
 We also have a multiplicative central limit theorem,
 where geometric means of (any) random variables are approximately log-normally distributed (under usual conditions).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
log-normal response in regression-like models
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:lognormalGAM"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We may want to model the mean via some linear model,
 for example when using a GLM or GAM
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Basic theory for log-normal linear models is covered in Section 3.2 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "crow_lognormal_1988"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 We decompose the mean as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X}\boldsymbol{\beta}$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times p$
\end_inset

 design matrix and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\beta}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-vector of coefficients to be estimated (where 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is the number of observations).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In practice,
 one can simply assume that the log-response is normally distributed and fit a GLM-a-like
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
GAM/GLMM/GAMM/etc.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 with a normal distribution.
 This model is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{E}(Y)=b^{\mu}=b^{\mathbf{X}\boldsymbol{\beta}},
\]

\end_inset

which is clearly modelling the geometric,
 rather than arithmetic mean (equivalently,
 we are modelling the median).
 This naturally extends to the case of random effects and therefore penalized smoothers (i.e.,
 GLMMs,
 GAMs and GAMMs).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An example of such an analysis in R is as follows:
\end_layout

