\begin_layout Section
Censored normal modelling
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Censored normal models are one kind of tobit model
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Tobin's probit
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 tends to refer to any censored regression model.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "goldberger_econometric_1964"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 where the response is censored in some way (in our case,
 that observations are below some detection threshold).
 Core to their formulation is the separation of the observation into censored and non-censored groups,
 where the censored likelihood contributions are evaluations of the cumulative distribution function (CDF) of the normal distribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Data takes the form of a triplet:
 
\begin_inset Formula $(y,\mathbf{x},c)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is the response,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 is the corresponding covariate vector (or in the case of a GAM,
 vector of basis function evaluations),
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is an indicator which is 1 if 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 was censored at some point 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 (i.e.,
 
\begin_inset Formula $y\leq C)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 otherwise.
 Since we do not know the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $y\leq C$
\end_inset

,
 we need to use the cumulative density function to evaluate the likelihood up to 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $y>C$
\end_inset

 we can use the usual likelihood function,
 since we then know 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

