\begin_layout Standard
For modelling censored normal variables,
 we conveniently know a lot about the CDF of the normal distribution;
 evaluation is therefore very simple and can use built-in functions in R.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Implementation in 
\family typewriter
mgcv
\family default
 via 
\family typewriter
cnorm()
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the 
\family typewriter
mgcv
\family default
 help file 
\family typewriter
?cnorm
\family default
:
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is the response with mean 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 and standard deviation 
\begin_inset Formula $w^{-1/2}\exp(\theta)$
\end_inset

,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $w^{1/2}(y-m)\exp(-\theta)$
\end_inset

 follows an 
\begin_inset Formula $N(0,1)$
\end_inset

 distribution.
 That is 
\begin_inset Formula $y\sim N(m,\exp(2\theta)/w)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is a single scalar for all observations.
 Observations may be left,
 interval or right censored or uncensored.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Combining approaches:
 censored log-normal distribution with arithmetic means for GAMs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can combine these approaches using a geometric mean by simply combining the approach for modelling log-normal data described in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "subsec:lognormalGAM"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 with the use of the censored normal distribution.
 In practice,
 that merely consists of using 
\family typewriter
mgcv::cnorm
\family default
 with the log-normally-distributed data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can post hoc correct predictions to use the arithmetic mean using a multivariate version of the correction in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:arithmean"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 These corrections lead to the following expressions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathbb{E}\left[g\left(\hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}}\right)\right] & =g\left(\hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}}\right)+\frac{1}{2n}\text{trace}\left(D^{2}g(\hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}})\Sigma\right)\quad\text{and}\nonumber \\
\hat{\text{Var}}\left[g\left(\hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}}\right)\right] & =\frac{1}{n}\left[Dg(\boldsymbol{\beta})\right]{}^{T}\Sigma(Dg(\boldsymbol{\beta}))+\frac{1}{2n^{2}}\text{trace}\left(D^{3}g(\boldsymbol{\beta})D^{2}g(\boldsymbol{\beta})\Sigma^{2}-\left[D^{2}g(\boldsymbol{\beta})\Sigma\right]^{2}\right)\label{eq:final-expect-var-1}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\boldsymbol{\beta})=b^{X\boldsymbol{\beta}}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is the base we are working in and 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is the design matrix for our model.
 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 indicates the derivative operator with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\beta}$
\end_inset

,
 with powers of 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 giving that order of derivative.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 is the posterior covariance matrix for 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\beta}$
\end_inset

 (see,
 e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "miller_bayesian_2025"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for further explanation of covariance matrices in the context of empirical Bayes modelling).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Derivations for these expressions are given in the Appendix.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Implementation of 
\family typewriter
mgcv
\family default
 family:
 
\family typewriter
clognorm()
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As the corrections in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:final-expect-var-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 can be applied post hoc,
 the easiest mechanism is via 
\family typewriter
mgcv
\family default
's per-family prediction functions.
 Since version 1.8-0,
 it has been possible to implement a 
\family typewriter
$predict
\family default
 function within a family (response distribution) function.
 When 
\family typewriter
mgcv::predict()
\family default
 is used with the 
\family typewriter
type=
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

response
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\family default
 flag set this function is called instead allowing for per-family special prediction functions.
 It is this mechanism that we exploit to implement seamless predictions using base 
\family typewriter
mgcv
\family default
 functions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\family typewriter
clognorm
\family default
 family is therefore implemented in 
\family typewriter
mgcvUtils
\family default
 as a copy of the 
\family typewriter
cnorm
\family default
 library with the addition of a 
\family typewriter
$predict
